# ovh\_vps\_distribution (Data Source)

Use this data source to retrieve the distribution currently installed on one of
your VPS. This complements `ovh_vps_distribution_template` (which describes a
catalog template) by reporting what is actually running on the VPS right now,
which is useful for drift detection and inventory.

## Example Usage

{{tffile "examples/data-sources/vps_distribution/example_1.tf"}}

## Argument Reference

* `service_name` - (Required) The internal name of your VPS (e.g. `vpsXXXXX.ovh.net`).

## Attributes Reference

* `id` - Template id of the installed distribution.
* `name` - Template name (e.g. `Debian 12`).
* `distribution` - Distribution family (e.g. `Debian`).
* `bit_format` - Architecture bit format (`32` or `64`). The OVH API returns
  this field as a JSON string; the provider exposes it as an integer.
* `locale` - Default locale of the installed distribution.
* `available_language` - Languages available for the installed distribution.

## Compatibility

This data source is part of the OVHcloud public VPS API schema, but the
underlying endpoint may not be implemented for every VPS lineup. Live
testing on a `vps-le-2-2-40` (2019v1) US instance returns
`404: Got an invalid (or empty) URL`. The endpoint is
exposed on EU and CA regions; on the US API it is only present for legacy VPS plans (pre-2019).

If you receive a 404 from this data source, your VPS plan likely does
not expose this endpoint. See [the OVHcloud VPS API console](https://api.us.ovhcloud.com/console/#/vps)
for what's available on your specific service.
